    </a>
    <h2>Pseudo Mercator</h2>
    <h3>Some observations: Tissot circles are the same shape so the shape of the countries hasn't been altered, but the circles at the upper and lower latitudes are much larger, indicating that the countries in those areas have increased in size on the map.</h3>
    <a href="./maps/Projection 3857.png">
    <img src="./maps/Projection 3857.png" alt="3857" width='500px'>
    </a>
    <h2>North Pole Azimuthal Equidistant</h2>
    <h3>Some observations</h3>
    <a href="./maps/Projection 102016.png">
    <img src="./maps/Projection 102016.png" alt="102016" width='500px'>
    </a>
    <h2>Sphere Winkle</h2>
    <h3>The map is rounder instead of having the countries be dislayed perfectly vertical.  The circles at the higher latitudes are closer in size to the equatorial ones, so we can see that the size of each country hasn't been altered extremely, but the shape of the circles at the poles is more oblong, so we know that the countries are distorted in shape.</h3>
    <a href="./maps/Projection 53018.png">
    <img src="./maps/Projection 53018.png" alt="53018" width='500px'>
    </a>
    <h2>World Equidistant</h2>
    <h3>This map appears to be looking at the Earth from the North Pole and expanding the countries around it. The shapes of the countries are very distorted, as you can see by the Tissot circles, which are extremely oblong and short the furhter you go from the pole.</h3>
    <a href="./maps/Projection 54027.png">
    <img src="./maps/Projection 54027.png" alt="54027" width='500px'>
    </a>
